Let $a$, $b$, and $c$ be the speeds at which $A$, $B$ and $C$ work, respectively. Also, let the piece of work be worth one unit of work. Then, using the information from the problem along with basic rate formulas, we obtain the following equations:
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{a}&=m*\frac{1}{b+c} \\
\frac{1}{b}&=n*\frac{1}{a+c} \\
\frac{1}{c}&=x*\frac{1}{a+b}
\end{align*}
These equations can be rearranged into the following:
\begin{align*}
\text{(i) } ma&=b+c \\
\text{(ii) } nb&=a+c \\
\text{(iii) } xc&=a+b \\
\end{align*}
Solving for $a$ in equation (i) gives us $a=\frac{b+c}{m}$. Substituting this expression for $a$ into equation (ii) yields:
\begin{align*}
nb&=\frac{b+c}{m}+c \\
mnb&=b+c+mc \\
(mn-1)b&=(m+1)c \\
b&=\frac{(m+1)c}{mn-1} 
\end{align*}
Finally, substituting our expressions for $a$ and $b$ into equation (iii) yields our final answer:
\begin{align*}
xc&=\frac{b+c}{m}+\frac{(m+1)c}{mn-1} \\
&=\frac{\frac{(m+1)c}{mn-1}+c}{m}+\frac{(m+1)c}{mn-1} \\
&=\frac{c}{m}(\frac{m+1+mn-1}{mn-1}+\frac{m^2+m}{mn-1}) \\
&=\frac{c}{m}(\frac{m^2+mn+2m}{mn-1}) \\
&=c(\frac{m+n+2}{mn-1})
\end{align*}
Thus, $x=\boxed{\frac{m+n+2}{mn-1}}$.

